            <fr:anchor>27991</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00KT</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00KT.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Counting bijections between finite sets">Counting <fr:link href="jms-00KR.xml" title="Bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijections</fr:link> between finite sets</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For all finite sets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, we have:</fr:p><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \mathord {\#}{\mathrm {Bij}{\mathopen {}\left (A,B\right )\mathclose {}}} =
 \begin {cases}
  0 &\text {if } \mathord {\#}{A}\not =\mathord {\#}{B}\\
  n!&\text {if } \mathord {\#}{A}=\mathord {\#}{B}=n
 \end {cases}
]]></fr:tex>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>23</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7593</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/4048</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-4048.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>A <fr:link href="jms-00KR.xml" title="Bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> between two sets is a way of associating <fr:em>precisely</fr:em> one element of the first set with <fr:em>precisely one</fr:em> element of the second set. These associations are embodied in the functions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\colon  B\to  A]]></fr:tex>, and the uniqueness of the associations is expressed by the conditio that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex> be simultaneously a <fr:link href="jms-00KS.xml" title="Section-retraction pair" addr="jms-00KS" type="local">section</fr:link> and a <fr:link href="jms-00KS.xml" title="Section-retraction pair" addr="jms-00KS" type="local">retraction</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>. Two sets of different cardinality can not be associated in this way, because there would always be left over elements that are not associated to any corresponding element. In this way, we see that a <fr:link href="jms-00KR.xml" title="Bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> exists between two sets if and only if they have the same cardinality.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Assuming two finite sets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A,B]]></fr:tex> with cardinality <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\#}{A}=\mathord {\#}{B}=n]]></fr:tex>, we must now count precisely how many bijections there are from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>. To construct such a bijection, we put all the elements <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> into a pile. Then, for each element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> we must successively choose and then <fr:em>discard</fr:em> an element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>; we have to discard the element because we are not allowed to choose it again (for, if we did, the association would not be bijective). At the beginning (“round <html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k=0]]></fr:tex>”</html:span>), there are <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> many choices we could make; in the next round <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k=1]]></fr:tex>, there are <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n-1]]></fr:tex> many choices that we could make; in the <html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>th</html:span> round, there are <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n-k]]></fr:tex> many choices that we could make. At the very end (after the <html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n-1]]></fr:tex>th</html:span> round), we shall have constructed a bijection after making <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n! = \prod _{0\leq  k<n} n-k]]></fr:tex> choices in total. Thus the number of distinct bijections from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n!]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
